defaultIntroductiondefault&#xa0;
default1. 
defaultThe Health &amp; Safety Executive (HSE) is 
defaultthe 
defaulthealth and safety regulator in 
defaultGreat Britain
default for work related activities, including those associated with shale gas.
default&#xa0;
default2. 
defaultHSE’s role is to ensure that operators of shale gas activities are adequately managing and controlling risks to the health and safety of people, whether workers, contractors, or members of the public. 
default&#xa0;
default3. 
defaultHSE has no role in setting energy policy and deciding what is the right mix of energy sources.  HSE is also not involved in 
defaultenvironmental protection, 
defaultlicensing or planning decisions related to shale gas.
default However, HSE does work collaboratively with the bodies responsible for overseeing such areas.
default&#xa0;
default4. 
defaultFor shale gas operations, HSE focuses on ensuring gas wells are designed, constructed, operated, maintained, and ultimately decommissioned to ensure that the flow of gases and
default 
defaultfluids in the well, whether fracking fluids or extracted gas or water is controlled and stays within the well. This is called ‘well integrity’ and is equally important for safety as well as environmental protection.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhatdefault are the main process safety hazardsdefault?default&#xa0;
default5. 
defaultThe e
defaultffective management and control of well integrity is key to safe shale gas operations and mitigating the risk of environmental pollution.
default&#xa0;
default6.  
defaultThe main
default hazard
default from shale gas operations
default is 
defaultthe 
defaultuncontrolled release of hydrocarbon gas due to a failure of the well structure, which may then reach a source of ignition leading to a fire or explosion. A well
default-
defaultdesigned and constructed well will reduce the risks of a release of 
defaultgas or 
defaultfluids
default 
defaultas low as is reasonably practicable. The actual level of risk varies, depending on how quickly and easily any release can be controlled, and on geological conditions. 
default&#xa0;
default7
default. 
defaultWhere there is a loss of well integrity, there is also the possibility of fracking fluids or water being released to the surrounding rock strata or at surface, which may have environmental consequences depending on the location of water aquifers.
default&#xa0;
default8
default. 
defaultThe occupational health and sa
defaultfety risks to workers from shale gas
default pilot activities are considerably lower than for other mineral extraction industries (e.g. coal mining and offshore oil and gas). People are generally working at ground level on sites with traditional health and safety risks comparable to a simple construction site, including 
defaultfalls or being hit by something.
