default&#xa0;defaultThe health and safety regulatory regimedefault&#xa0;
default9
default. 
defaultHSE’s regulatory regime is long established
default and is 
defaultgoal 
defaultsetting. 
defaultThe 
defaultgeneral duties under the 
defaultHealth and Safety at Work Act 
defaultetc 
default1974 (HSWA) 
defaultrequire 
defaultrisks to workers and the public to be reduced so far
default as is reasonable practicable. 
defaultThis is 
defaultsupplement
defaulted
default with more specific regulations particular to 
defaultthe 
defaultextraction of gas and oil through wells, which includes shale gas operations.   
default&#xa0;
default10
default. 
defaultThe specific regulations are:
default&#xa0;
defaultThese regulations require notifications to be made to HSE about the design, construction and operation of wells
default,
default and a health and safety plan which sets out how risks are managed on site;
default and
default 
defaultThese regulations include specific requirements for all wells, whether onshore or offshore, and include well integrity provisions which apply throughout the life of shale gas wells. They also require a well operator to provide HSE with regular reports of any activities on the well and to appoint an independent well examiner to undertake regular assessments of well integrity.
default 
default&#xa0;
default1
default1
default. 
defaultThis combination of duties ensures that HSE is provided with information at key stages in the lifecycle of a well and allows 
defaultHSE
default to assess whether risks are being adequately controlled and, if not, to intervene.  
default&#xa0;
defaultHow does HSE conduct its interventions?default&#xa0;
default12
default. 
defaultHSE’s intervention approach has two elements. 
default&#xa0;
default13
default. 
defaultThe first has been to contribute to the development of best practice standards for the industry as a whole with the 
defaultUnited Kingdom Onshore Operators Group
default.
default These standards 
defaultwere published in February 2013.  Such guidance, and existing industry codes dealing with well design and operations, sets clear expectation between HSE and operators as to how the general goal of reducing risks so far is reasonably practicable can be met. 
default&#xa0;
default14
default. 
defaultThe second element is to focus HSE interventions with particular sites and operators on the key risk control measure of ensuring well integrity. For this, HSE uses its team of expert wells engineers who cover all types of hydrocarbon wells both on and offshore. As an oil or gas well is a complex engineered construction, most of which is not accessible to visual inspection, HSE takes a lifecycle approach to well integrity. 
default&#xa0;
default15
default. 
defaultThis lifecycle 
defaultapproach 
defaultconsists of: 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis allows HSE to assess the well design before construction starts. This is a key phase of work where the vast majority of issues likely to have an
default impact on well integrity
default will be identified and addressed by the well operator. It includes ensuring that safety features are incorporated into the design.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThis provides HSE with the assurance that the operator is constructing and operating the well as described in the notification
default.  W
defaulthen they are not, HSE can take the appropriate action.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis includes site inspections to assess well integrity during the operational phase
default. 
defaultF
defaultor new and first time shale gas operators
default,
default HSE and 
defaultthe Environment Agency 
defaultwill meet and advise them of their duties and conduct a joint inspection of their key operations. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe independent well examinerdefault&#xa0;
default16
default. 
defaultHSE’s regulatory
default approach is supplemented by the requirement 
defaultin DCR 
defaultfor an independent well examiner to assess 
defaultwell 
defaultdesign, construction and maintenance. The well examiner is an independent competent person separate from the immediate line management of the well operations 
defaultbeing
default examin
defaulted
default. The well examiner can be an employee of the operating company or
default, as is normally 
defaultthe case for 
defaultUK
default onshore wells
default, 
defaulta contractor. 
default&#xa0;
default17
default. 
defaultThe examiner’s task is to review the proposed and actual well operations to confirm they meet the operator’s policies and procedures, comply with DCR and follow good industry practice. This may include periodic site visits.
default&#xa0;
default18
default. 
defaultHSE checks that the operator has these arrangements in place. The well examination scheme and involvement of the well examiner is for the complete lifecycle of the well from design through to final plugging and decommissioning.
